Meanings":[{"name":"d'Amiens","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: from the personal name <i>Damien</i>, French form of   Damian  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Damian","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Francisco, Juan, Jose, Pedro, Alberto, Armando, Carlos, Cesar, Elena, Felipe, Lourdes, Luis.","Spanish (<b>Damián</b>), German, Romanian, Italian, and Polish: from the personal name <i>Damián</i>, <i>Damian</i> respectively, Greek <i>Damianos</i> (from <i>damazein</i> ‘to subdue’), Latin <i>Damianus</i>. Saint Damian was an early Christian saint martyred in Cilicia in  AD  303 under the emperor Domitian, together with his brother Cosmas (see   Kosmas  ). In some accounts the brothers are said to have been doctors, and together they were regarded as the patrons of physicians and apothecaries. A later Saint Damian lived in the 7th–8th centuries and was bishop of Pavia; he may have had some influence on the popularity of the personal name in Italy. This surname is also found among Rusyns (Lemkos).","In some cases probably also French (southern France and Lorraine): from a variant of the personal name   Damien  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: The Scripture name, in Hebrew, Adham, signifying 'man;' literally earthy, red earth; Rudolph, however, says the name in Ethiopic means ' to be fair, beautiful.' Hence the nurse-name Addy, little Adam."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Adam I d'Amiens was born in 1072, in Amiens, Somme, Picardie, France. He married Béatrix D'Ath in 1100, in France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1136, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1072–1136":"1072–1136","1072–1150":"1072–1150","1102–Female":"1102–Surnud","1104–Male":"1104–Surnud","1108–1147":"1108–1147","1104":"1104","1136":"1136","1147":"1147","1102":"1102","1100":"1100","1150":"1150","1072":"1072","1108":"1108","Amiens, Somme, Pi